ls is a tool used to print out stats about files in the currect directory. Any attempt to parse the output of ls is VERY ill-advised, since there is simply no way of making sure you get what you expect out of it. This is because ls uses spaces, tabs, or newlines to delimit its output. *All* of these can possibly be a part of a filename! As such, you might be splitting some filenames in half by trying to delimit it by either of these. for i in * is
